text:
qanon fans are applying this same participatory behavior that we have celebrated in fiction fandom to real-world political drama. and why not? the boundaries between politics and entertainment have been collapsing for years. the entire trump presidency operates like reality tv, completely divorced from any real stakes or substance.

thatâ€™s what makes this all so terrifying. do these people really believe that tom hanks and hillary clinton are personally running a massive pedophilia ring? really??? but consider this: trump announced at a rally this week that the farmers being harmed by his stupid trade war had told him â€œwe can take it.â€ no actual farmers said that to him. we all know that. but itâ€™s a little thing, just part of the story we are all interacting with.

the pulsating heart of the qanon theory is not a lunatic fringe denying the real consequences of a failing presidency. the heart of it is a devoted fan base constructing elaborate theories to make the story more fun and engaging. and if you start from the premise that nothing government does matters, then itâ€™s easy to come along for the ride. thereâ€™s no real difference between hillary clinton and the smoke monster. theyâ€™re both just characters on the television.

thatâ€™s what alarms me most about the growth of qanon. itâ€™s not that these people are unhinged and possibly armed. itâ€™s that weâ€™ve lost the capacity to treat civics, governance, and public affairs as though they have actual stakes with actual consequences. the premise of the trump presidency is that nothing matters, so you should root for your side and heckle the opposing team. he encourages his supporters to treat democrats and journalists like a rival fan base.

david karpf

text:
qanon fans are applying this same participatory behavior that we have celebrated in fiction fandom to real-world political drama. and why not? the boundaries between politics and entertainment have been collapsing for years. the entire trump presidency operates like reality tv, completely divorced from any real stakes or substance.

thatâ€™s what makes this all so terrifying. do these people really believe that tom hanks and hillary clinton are personally running a massive pedophilia ring? really??? but consider this: trump announced at a rally this week that the farmers being harmed by his stupid trade war had told him â€œwe can take it.â€ no actual farmers said that to him. we all know that. but itâ€™s a little thing, just part of the story we are all interacting with.

the pulsating heart of the qanon theory is not a lunatic fringe denying the real consequences of a failing presidency. the heart of it is a devoted fan base constructing elaborate theories to make the story more fun and engaging. and if you start from the premise that nothing government does matters, then itâ€™s easy to come along for the ride. thereâ€™s no real difference between hillary clinton and the smoke monster. theyâ€™re both just characters on the television.

thatâ€™s what alarms me most about the growth of qanon. itâ€™s not that these people are unhinged and possibly armed. itâ€™s that weâ€™ve lost the capacity to treat civics, governance, and public affairs as though they have actual stakes with actual consequences. the premise of the trump presidency is that nothing matters, so you should root for your side and heckle the opposing team. he encourages his supporters to treat democrats and journalists like a rival fan base.

david karpf

text:
in the wake of recent relevations that have broken me into a million pieces and have left me confused, frustrated and angry, here's my two cents on the matter. 
sexual harrassment is a real issue. and justifying sexual harassment by blaming it on how men â€˜dont get the sex talkâ€™ or are â€˜sexually frustratedâ€™, is a shitty excuse. teach everyone earlier on, specially your boys and men, that nothing, nothing at all justifies their harrasment no matter how they try to phrase it. dont let them make the excuse of â€˜we were unaware of where to draw the lineâ€™ and teach them about consent beforehand.

it will never be acceptable to invalidate the terrifying experiences of those who have been through hell by saying men need to express their sexual urges somewhere. well, iâ€™ve got some breaking news for you: women are humans too. shocking right? we have urges too. yet how many go up to men and make them uncomfortable in every place possible? 
i'm not saying it doesn't happen, but using the "women harrass too" card to justify or nullify male harassment is over. 
we are done being quiet. men, do better.

text:
qanon fans are applying this same participatory behavior that we have celebrated in fiction fandom to real-world political drama. and why not? the boundaries between politics and entertainment have been collapsing for years. the entire trump presidency operates like reality tv, completely divorced from any real stakes or substance.

thatâ€™s what makes this all so terrifying. do these people really believe that tom hanks and hillary clinton are personally running a massive pedophilia ring? really??? but consider this: trump announced at a rally this week that the farmers being harmed by his stupid trade war had told him â€œwe can take it.â€ no actual farmers said that to him. we all know that. but itâ€™s a little thing, just part of the story we are all interacting with.

the pulsating heart of the qanon theory is not a lunatic fringe denying the real consequences of a failing presidency. the heart of it is a devoted fan base constructing elaborate theories to make the story more fun and engaging. and if you start from the premise that nothing government does matters, then itâ€™s easy to come along for the ride. thereâ€™s no real difference between hillary clinton and the smoke monster. theyâ€™re both just characters on the television.

thatâ€™s what alarms me most about the growth of qanon. itâ€™s not that these people are unhinged and possibly armed. itâ€™s that weâ€™ve lost the capacity to treat civics, governance, and public affairs as though they have actual stakes with actual consequences. the premise of the trump presidency is that nothing matters, so you should root for your side and heckle the opposing team. he encourages his supporters to treat democrats and journalists like a rival fan base.

david karpf

text:
@regrann from @thehealedwomanfoundation - the thought was to wait till next year to start our projects as a foundation. but there are women and girls who have been suffering from abuses and the effects hoping for a glimpse of hope and someone who at least understands and will believe them. waiting would mean leaving them to hurt till next year...no.
.
.
with our project, rescue the girl child, we will be visiting primary and secondary schools all over nigeria to educate female students about sexual abuse, child trafficking and other forms of abuse that can affect them. with this, we want to get to meet girls who are victims and offer them help in the form of counseling and by partnering with other organizations, get them legal help too.
.
.
our first tour will be next month, november 2018. our target is 20 schools within lagos and ogun states.
.
.
rescue the girl child tour needs partnership (most important), volunteering and donations to take it further. our target is to reach out to girls in all schools in nigeria.
.
.
to partner with us, volunteer, or make a donation, send an email to admin@thehealedwoman.org or call +2347069403717
.
.

text:
they said it was a curse. 
i almost believed them. 
shame for my beauty. 
shame for my strength. 
shame for my passion.
shame for my anger.
shame for my grace. 
luscious like a georgia peach on a warm summer day. 
i tried to hide my appetite for dirty books and lace. 
everything that made me sizzle,
they tried to erase. 
i almost let them. 
their lies were dipped in poison.
disguised as the only way. 
not anymore. 
not today.
name: Goddess Medicine

at the center for women and families, we work every day to advocate for those who have lost their voice. itâ€™s tough work, but people like charlotte are why we do it. 
charlotte was stabbed repeatedly by her husband and left for dead. miraculously, she survived the trauma and this event led her to the safety of the center for women and families.

working with our advocates, charlotte made plans for her future, plans that included taking care of herself and her five children. she completed a two-year training program while working full time. she was able to start thinking about safe and affordable housing and could live the reality she had once only imaginedâ€”a life free from the violence she had thought would never end. =====================================
our advocates are available 24/7, 1-844-237-2331.

text:
after the working mother awards luncheon yesterday in chicago, i moderated a table discussion of in-house counsel and law firm leaders on #metoo and #implicitbias. the working mother research institute and the aba law journal surveyed over 3,000 employees of businesses and law firms on these issues. key report results: *61% of women believe men hold a disproportionate share of power in their organization. *54% of men and only 23% of women believe both genders are allies in reaching gender equality. *men are nervous about 1:1 professional interactions with women. when asked if these relationships are at risk because of the perception of unacceptable behavior, 56% of men agreed vs 35% of women. *68% of women reported experiencing workplace sexual harassment vs 19% of men. *27% of women believe their complaints were taken seriously vs 42% of men. *52% of women failed to report their complaint believing it would negatively impact their careers vs 27% of men. *45% of the women said they have no confidence that senior leadership would address the issue vs 24% of men. 
do any of these statistics shock you? our roundtable discussed proposed solutions to these issues. i'd love to hear what you or your organization is doing to combat these obstacles.

text:
+about last night+
.
.
nurturing, nourishing and natural; powerful, potent and pertinent; frustrating, funny and flawed. that was last night...
.
.
.
i was fortunate enough to be one of 13 beautiful women gathered for an evening of heart and womb-based gloriousness in the amazing @slc_london hosted by @rebecca_wilson_ . if you donâ€™t know rebeccaâ€™s work, check it out immediately! so powerful and important for womenkind right now. reconnection with our cycles, our creativity and our power centres. it was an amazing evening of meditation, yoga, mantra and self-love. a group of women celebrating not only womanhood, but the balance between the divine feminine and the divine masculine. that men should be celebrated as well as women. that feminism isnâ€™t about women â€˜taking back powerâ€™ but reclaiming their place in the world alongside and in connection with men. .
.
. 
afterwards, my friend and i wanted to compare notes so we popped into the local pub to catch up... whereupon i was groped. in full view of a room of people, by a man who thought this was very funny and should be applauded by his friends. talk about juxtaposition. .
.
.
time for an attitude change. surely. on both sides. has the #metoo movement had an impact, yes, and it needs to continue, to grass roots. to the locker rooms, the water coolers, the pubs and clubs. i am not a possession or an object; i am not here for your delectation. unless i choose to be, and believe me you would know. .
.
.
as a single woman in a society that claims to be maturing in its attitudes to the gender divide, it concerns me to still see this lack of understanding and respect. and please donâ€™t misunderstand me, this is not a sexist rant. there is fault on all sides. but hey, people, all of us need to continue to create more understanding of each other. and, above all, letâ€™s be kind. .
.
.
#bekind #womenunderstandingmen #menunderstandingwomen #sensitivityisok #respect #divinefeminine #divinemasculine #awakenedunderstanding #wombconnection #wombhealing #femaleancestry #reconnecttoyourpower #transformationalcoach #writer #healer #presenter image courtesy of @elephantjournal

text:
as with many mainstream movements that become co-opted by outside interests, the #metoo movement has neglected to acknowledge the unique and specific history that black women in this country share. though founder @taranajaneen has fought valiantly to remind us all about honoring the experiences of sexual assault victims and meeting them at the various intersections of identity where they may stand, many of our stories go unheard. the black womanâ€™s body has always been politicized, commodified, exploited and forsaken...stripping so many of their own bodily autonomy. from slavery, through jim crow to anita hill, to tarana burke...itâ€™s time to begin honoring and holding space for black women when discussing rape, consent and bodily autonomy.

girl.. it's a violent world.. i believe my art is my medium to connect and communicate with the world around me. this image is my understanding and support to the #metoo campaign that has been creating massive waves. its a fact that the patriarchal eyes are still out there watching, hunting and we can't stop emphasising this fact that a change is very much needed. 
let our future generations be free from fear of the stare.

text:
today i will be talking about a very horrifying reality of this society. a woman wether fully covered or even if she is in western clothes is never safe. actually never safe from the men out there who awkwardly stare them from top to bottom. being a woman this sometimes is really annoying and many of us think, its our fault. 
most of the time we have to go through social anxiety and pressure. this phase is literally so traumatic. if we need to change the way we dress but the question is change to what? abaya ? and the ones who wear abaya, what do they need to change? still those eyes stare them as if they have committed a crime. should we stop going out and give up ? 
no, never because itâ€™s not us who need to be changed! this society needs to be changed, its standards require a huge change because a woman wether covered or uncovered faces the same harassment everyday. it is obvious, this ainâ€™t our fault. these men who make it difficult for us to achieve something need to be changed and need to realise. not us . every women has the right to speak against this! stand up girls! shout back to the filthy standards of our society. live your life as you want to because you donâ€™t have to change  because of anyone. realise this ainâ€™t your fault, itâ€™s their fault! .
.
.
.
.

text:
they say, picture says thousand words, at times the expression that you notice on the pictures says much more than that...! this was from last evening and really sorry to post them late. actresses like renuka shahane, filmmakers like sonali bose, kabir khan shared their views on the broader aspect of #metoomovement . while renuka emphasised on how it is important to separate art from the artist who is a human being and could be misorganist, sonali said how discrimination on women is embedded in our culture!! very interestingly, in the opening film titled mard ko dard nahi hota, director vasan bala is presenting female characters in a way more substantial manner that of her male counterpart. well, the ray of hope is, if such films are coming from newage storyteller like bala, it means, the future if indian cinema is in good hand!! #instablogging

text:
i was playing on the street near my home, with my friends. when the time for lunch neared, we all felt hungry and slowly one by one started to leave to our homes. i was the last one to leave. all of a sudden, one teenage boy blocked my way and asked my name, i barely remember his face. i didn't answer him, since maa told me not to speak with strangers, especially with boys.

i tried to walk away from him, he held my hand firmly; i shrugged. i shouted for help but no one was around. he quickly groped my breast and ran away.

i couldn't react. i stood there still, with tears flooding my eyes. when i reached home, mom asked me "what's wrong diya?". "i fell down while playing and hurt myself." i said. the first-ever lie of my life.

that night i couldn't sleep. i felt degraded. it was disgusting. why did he do that to me? why? what made him to do that? what is the fun in groping my breast and running away? will he do this to his mother or other girls? a thousand questions popped in my mind. without my conciousness, my eyes were flooding, i can't control my tears.

days passed like this and one day, me and my friends were playing on the same street. and when i went to fetch some water, i saw one of my friend sitting under the neem tree, weeping and looking worried. i asked her why she is crying. she said nothing and signalled me to go away. when i turned back, i could see that same boy who harassed me running at a distance. my nerves freezed for a second, i could sense what might've happened to my friend.

that day i realised, i'm not the only victim. and over the period of time, i got to know that not only women, even men are also sexually abused. all the girls/boys, i've met in my life so far, had a similar or different sexual harasement backstory. some of them were really intense.
.
"got it? you shouldn't be like mom or the rest of the girls/boys, whenever someone sexually abuse or harass you, raise your voice, file a complaint, drag him/her before the law and make him/her plead for their life on your feet." i mused to the soul residing in my womb.

written by - aravind subramani

#trynewwritings #aravindsubramani #creativewriting #ustoo #readers #writers #metoo

text:
the shrine is no longer divine now
the aura is no more pristine now 
light scares me
as if someone stares me 
particulate fear
diffused far and near
when the fog is not clear
my screams none can hear
mighty boulders churned my virginity 
thunder roars besmirched serenity.

my eyes flowed 
and so do others
from mountaintop 
as rivers till seawaters 
which have turned to oceans 
seasoned with the flavors 
with flavors of female feticide
with flavors of dowry
with flavors of rape
with flavors of molestation 
with flavors of what not

sooner or later 
if you pursue to smear
oh men, your spotless terrain
shall be drowned by oceans and rain 
with my tears of suffering.
how will you keep surviving?

humanity has begun to decline now 
the aura is no more pristine now. ~Â©sb @writersb_

text:
i was playing on the street near my home, with my friends. when the time for lunch neared, we all felt hungry and slowly one by one started to leave to our homes. i was the last one to leave. all of a sudden, one teenage boy blocked my way and asked my name, i barely remember his face. i didn't answer him, since maa told me not to speak with strangers, especially with boys.

i tried to walk away from him, he held my hand firmly; i shrugged. i shouted for help but no one was around. he quickly groped my breast and ran away.

i couldn't react. i stood there still, with tears flooding my eyes. when i reached home, mom asked me "what's wrong diya?". "i fell down while playing and hurt myself." i said. the first-ever lie of my life.

that night i couldn't sleep. i felt degraded. it was disgusting. why did he do that to me? why? what made him to do that? what is the fun in groping my breast and running away? will he do this to his mother or other girls? a thousand questions popped in my mind. without my conciousness, my eyes were flooding, i can't control my tears.

days passed like this and one day, me and my friends were playing on the same street. and when i went to fetch some water, i saw one of my friend sitting under the neem tree, weeping and looking worried. i asked her why she is crying. she said nothing and signalled me to go away. when i turned back, i could see that same boy who harassed me running at a distance. my nerves freezed for a second, i could sense what might've happened to my friend.

that day i realised, i'm not the only victim. and over the period of time, i got to know that not only women, even men are also sexually abused. all the girls/boys, i've met in my life so far, had a similar or different sexual harasement backstory. some of them were really intense.
.
"got it? you shouldn't be like mom or the rest of the girls/boys, whenever someone sexually abuse or harass you, raise your voice, file a complaint, drag him/her before the law and make him/her plead for their life on your feet." i mused to the soul residing in my womb.

written by - aravind subramani

text:
new delhi: gerakan #metoo hingga saat ini masih heboh di india. banyak kasus pelecehan seksual yang diungkap dan melibatkan para pelaku industri hiburan, termasuk fotografer bernama raja bajaj (rajesh v bajaj), ayah dari sheena bajaj (pemainÂ thapki). dilansir dariÂ bombay times, rabu (24/10/2018), raja bajaj dituduh telah melakukan pelecehan seksual terhadap aktris sonal vengurlekar pada 2012 ketika sonal masih baru di dunia tv.

sonal menceritakan saat itu ia mendapat panggilan audisi oleh raja. namun karena belum bisa berdialog dengan baik, raja mengajaknya ikut kegiatan pemotretannya agar paham dengan profesi aktris yang ingin digelutinya. mereka kemudian datang ke sebuah resort di khopoli.

meski sudah ada seorang gadis yang jadi model, raja tetap meminta sonal ganti baju dan memakai krim khusus agar bentuk payudaranya bagus. raja bahkan mengikutinya hingga ruang ganti dan memakaikan krim itu dengan paksa. selain itu raja juga mendatangi kamar sonal untuk mengajarinya mantra agar cepat terkenal, dan memintanya duduk telanjang di depannya.

raja bajaj membantah tuduhan tersebut. ia menyebut telah menyuruh sonal pulang bersama model yang ternyata tak cocok untuk pemotretannya. tapi sonal menolak. sonal juga satu kamar dengan para kru sehingga tak mungkin para kru tidak menyadari kehadiran raja.

raja juga menuduh manajer resort tersebut yang justru memerasnya dengan kasus ini, termasuk sonal yang mendatangi rumahnya untuk meminta uang sebesar rs3 lakhs, lalu turun menjadi rs1,5 lakhs. .
.
source by : mediyaa
. .
follow : @dunia_india @dunia_india2 .
.

text:
the thought was to wait till next year to start our projects as a foundation. but there are women and girls who have been suffering from abuses and the effects hoping for a glimpse of hope and someone who at least understands and will believe them. waiting would mean leaving them to hurt till next year...no.
.
.
with our project, rescue the girl child, we will be visiting primary and secondary schools all over nigeria to educate female students about sexual abuse, child trafficking and other forms of abuse that can affect them. with this, we want to get to meet girls who are victims and offer them help in the form of counseling and by partnering with other organizations, get them legal help too.
.
.
our first tour will be next month, november 2018. our target is 20 schools within lagos and ogun states.
.
.
rescue the girl child tour needs partnership (most important), volunteering and donations to take it further. our target is to reach out to girls in all schools in nigeria.
.
.
to partner with us, volunteer, or make a donation, send an email to admin@thehealedwoman.org or call +2347069403717
.
.
cac/it/no 118484

text:
#metoo is rising in pakistan. what can you as an individual do to sustain it as a movement rather than just a campaign in our society?
.
. ğŸ“£fight the ignorance in your own family.
support your sisters and friends. give them the confidence to share whatever they feel with you. remind them you are here whenever you can and show up when they need you, be it inside the home or outside. ğŸ“£ stand by the survivors even if the accused person is your friend. listen to the survivors. give their trauma the worth it deserves and question your media if it does not do the same. ğŸ“£ share what you know about self defense with women around you and help the men around you to understand what in their behavior is okay and what isn't. teach them accountability. ğŸ“£ acknowledge the existence of #lgbtq+ people in our society, understand their rights, and be inclusive of their perspective, their stories and their experiences in your conversations. ğŸ“£ give the men around you enough space to be vulnerable. assure them that they won't be judged if they talk about their experiences of being bullied, harassed and assaulted with you. ğŸ“£ don't judge the survivors for not speaking up before. don't force them to share their stories if they don't feel they are ready. ğŸ“£ dare to imagine the realities inhabited by our religious minorities. empathize. ğŸ“£ talk to the people around you about regret. have they been a participant of a culture that normalizes #sexualharassment? have they caused emotional harm to someone socially/ emotionally / physically weaker than them that could have harmed their self respect? do they regret it? if they could go back in time, how differently will they deal with the situation? â–¶have you tried taking any of these steps? how did it turn out for you?
/
/

as of my experience so far. i have come across good men. i also had experienced filthy boys to but i had my family & friends to back me up.

i can only say that.
it depends on the word no.
kindness nowadays is taken advantage.

i learned to say no.
i hope that you guys too would say this.
but only to those who exploit you.
not to chores, homework, study, etc...
- irene j

in daily life, i am a highly, functioning individual therefore my internal angst goes unnoticed by the casual observer. however, my life has never been free of drama; drama is drawn to me like lint to a sweater. a product of my environment, i was born into and raised under domestic violence. as a result, my life was shattered from the start. consequently, i careened through life broken---feeling ashamed and anxious about everything. nevertheless, the swirl of drama is easily detectable by those who come closer and has cost me dearly. one long-gone acquaintance said her husband wondered why my life was so drama prone. it was sentiments like this, often more unspoken than spoken, which caused me to run - to hide in shame and panic. i felt embarrassed by the constant flow of â€˜heavyâ€™, which always streamed from my life. many a-time, i walked away from friendships because i felt my life carried too much weight. it is only now, after much self-analysis, that i have claimed my drama-filled life. in so doing, at 55 years of age, i am beginning to live a more  peaceful and authentic life. claim your dramaâ€” set yourself free!~~~#authenticity #real #reality #woke #speak #speaklife #honesty #truth #nodrama #healing #recovery #survivors #metoo #woke #light #spreadinglove #clarity #awareness presence #women #journey #change #artphotography #stories #rise #empower #personalgrowth #yoga #yogainspiration #yogacommunityğŸ™ğŸ½for likes and follows!â¤ï¸âœ¨âœ¨â¤ï¸ğŸ’«

i stood waiting for my boyfriend
to get something in the other
room, so near i could hear his voice
through the open door
chatting to another friend who had 
come with us to this house of a man
we didn't know the reason 
wiped away by what i can recall 
of that day being grabbed
held 
a mouth pushed against mine-
-violence-
'don't tell'-
didn't he say 'don't tell'?-
pushed down into the folds of time.
fear he smeared all over me
and guilt. 
through a glass i watch that young girl,
a survivor who 
fought her way out of the rubble 
of circumstance, watch her not
crumble, watch her not shatter
no
never
a mousetrap won't trip her up
she survived an earthquake.

text:
i used my pepper spray for the first time around this date last year. hereâ€™s what led to it and what came afterwards.
- my creepy neighbour-cum-stalker would questions like â€œhave you seen my guinea pig?, will you bring your dog to my home and help me find my turtle?â€
- i dismissed him.
- angered boy (apparent dog lover) now has the audacity to ring my door bell and abuse me for feeding stray dogs.
- i report this to the society. thereâ€™s a meeting. he apologises. we ask the father, â€œnow that you know your son has serious behavioural problems, what will you do about it? the father solemnly replies, â€œi will make him do a satyanarayan puja.â€
- the puja obviously didnâ€™t pay off.
- two months later, at 12 midnight, he had been splashing water on sleeping dogs and threw away the crate and blanket that i kept for a litter of newborn puppies. - i asked him to stop, he hurled abuses at me and so did i. he held my hand, pushed me against the wall and tried to overpower me. - luckily i didnâ€™t leave my home alone at night to face this idiot without a pepper spray. i used it liberally, full on his face.
- people stood in their balconies, watching amusingly. i didnâ€™t want to go home fearing that heâ€™ll be lurking in the corridor. - kapil sane (or insane) comes back again and tells me that even if i go to the cops, i canâ€™t harm him.
- the cops at dahanukar colony police station were extremely supportive and picked up the culprit in no time. - his parents walked in and opened a series of verbal attacks. their point being, a girl worried about safety should not step out alone at night. as if it gives their son the right to touch me. - when they sense that theyâ€™ve landed in deeper trouble by misbehaving in front of the cops, they plead me not to file a complaint. - hereâ€™s what the senior police inspector told me, and what every girl should remember. he said, â€œknow that the ordeal doesnâ€™t end here. if you file a complaint, i have the legal right to protect you from any further harassment. if you donâ€™t, even i am powerless.â€ #metoo is not always a case of sexual assault. most often it is habitual disrespect towards women. because thatâ€™s how these scums have been brought up.

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
for those 87 million people probably wondering what was actually done with their data, i went back to christopher wylie, the ex-cambridge analytica employee who blew the whistle on the companyâ€™s problematic operations in the observer. according to wylie, all you need to know is a little bit about data science, a little bit about bored rich women, and a little bit about human psychology.

step one, he says, over the phone as he scrambles to catch a train: - when youâ€™re building an algorithm, you first need to create a training set. that is: no matter what you want to use fancy data science to discover, you first need to gather the old-fashioned way. before you can use facebook likes to predict a personâ€™s psychological profile, you need to get a few hundred thousand people to do a 120-question personality quiz.

the â€œtraining setâ€ refers, then, to that data in its entirety: the facebook likes, the personality tests, and everything else you want to learn from. most important, it needs to contain your â€œfeature setâ€: - the underlying data that you want to make predictions on, wylie says. - in this case, itâ€™s facebook data, but it could be, for example, text, like natural language, or it could be clickstream data â€“ the complete record of your browsing activity on the web. those are all the features that you want to [use to] predict. at the other end, you need your target variables, the things that youâ€™re trying to predict for. so in this case, personality traits or political orientation, or what have you.

alex hern
the guardian

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking â€˜ugh. totally uglyâ€™ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr

text:
the chorus of "me too" - my latest painting and my first attempt at abstract.

the chorus of â€œme tooâ€ is not a cry for help or a pleading call. it is for women who wish to have their voices heard above them all as they no longer feel the need to keep their silence sealed.

for too many years, the world around us has been deaf and blind. so listen to the accusations now and keep them in your mind.

for women are not broken little things and when they come together their voices sing. while you were so locked in your world, you missed the war inside her head streaming all that violence and you missed her spark.

you never saw that they are quite resilient and you can no longer quiet their ring. you never saw that she was growing from the ashes that you left, knowing she was suffering.

so carry on women, keep your voices booming loud and clear.

and you all, keep your senses open for the woman closest to you is ready to whisper, â€œme too", even when no one else is near.
.
.
.
.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
amplify her will be at spark animation today at 4pm to speak about how in a post #metoo world where women are finally speaking up, more content with real stories for women is needed. this panel will discuss the collaborative and feminine approach to creating amplify her. 
throughout the panel, we will preview work, show behind-the-scenes clips of the process and discuss the details of how 25 women came together to answer the question: what unique gifts can female creators offer our culture? 
speakers will be jenn strom, lindsay ishihiro, nicole sorochan & tammy dubinsky.

text: #onewomanoneday end of my first week in china/ hong kong and i am catching up on news before my babies arrive in a couple of hours, in particular the latest #metoo stories on philip green and googleâ€™s disclosure that it has seen off 48 employees accused of sexual harassment, some with eye watering pay offs.  the philip green story throws up the thorny issues of ndas and parliamentary privilege.  on balance, i think there is enough of a public interest aspect to a story involving a recipient of a knight hood, but it concerns me that at least 2 of his victims did not want to breach the nda; i hope the fallout does not suck them into the public domain.  the alternative to ndas is compromise agreements that do not restrict the victims from discussing the allegations in public (but would still keep the amount of compensation confidential) or litigation.  the latter can be traumatic for victims, the former is possible but it requires companies to be open about their cultures and take appropriate actions against the alleged perpetrators (where the allegations are upheld - some are not but compromise agreements still ensue, which is acceptable provided there is no duress on the alleged victim). today i profile vera lui, a hong kong hurdler who last year kickstarted the #metoo story in hong kong with her disclosure that she had been sexually assaulted by her coach when she was 13.  so brave. so sad but not unexpected that so many stories are coming out of the woodwork.  but will we learn from this ? the only way is to have consequences and that means investigating these allegations no matter the passage of time and prosecuting where there is evidence to do so.  #metoo #veralui #hongkong #philipgreen #google

text:
a calm mind has the power to heal.
.
.
.
.
rest.
then rise.
.
we here at the [re]centered movement are proud to announce our very first collaborative series for the blog. in this series we will examine the effects of trauma on the brain and on the body. we will then explore our distinct approaches to treating, managing and healing its symptoms. we will be hearing from an acupuncturist, an ayurvedic practitioner, a reiki healer, a naturopathic doctor, a neuromuscular conditioning specialist, a trauma informed yoga teacher, a clinical psychologist and an md who specializes in integrated medicine.
.
our hope is that by sharing our distinct perspectives and approaches, we will help everyone including other professionals gain a deeper understanding, not only of the biological changes that take place following a traumatic experience, but also of the benefits that can be gained by taking a multi-disciplinary approach to treatment.
ğŸ“· by @whiteandwarren
.

and so shall we.

and so shall we.

god cries with the masses of starving people, despises growing disparity between ritch and poor, demands justice for workers in the marketplace. 
and so shall we. 
today is the day
god deplores violence in our homes and street, rebukes the worldâ€™s warring madness, humbles the powerful and lifts up the lowly. 
and so shall we.

today is the day

and so shall we. 
today is the day 
god brings good news to the poor, proclaims release to the captives, gives sight to the blind, and sets the oppressed free. 
and so shall we. ...

text:
tell your stories. tell your truth. keep talking. get mad. keep supporting other abuse survivors. a year after the birth of the #metoo movement, much has changed and nothing has changed. victim blaming is on the rise again having seen and experienced it myself from fans, friends, and other people @adamcroasdell has enlisted towards myself and his other victims shows me how malicious and unsafe this world can be for victims. using young impressionable fans to shame and silence his victims shows how far we have to go to make victims feel safe from these abusers. actions from them and him is #whyididntreport on top of living in fear of him and their threats. my silence gave him a thirst for more and younger victims. i realize and know wholeheartedly he will never stop. his fans, friends, and family are his accomplices by victim shaming and he shows no remorse for the pain he causes he feels proud. in other words, if youâ€™re waiting for them to make an apology, forget it. these men might regret getting caught. but expressing true remorse about the damage they caused isnâ€™t forthcoming. what most of them havenâ€™t lost is the conviction that since they are either celebrities, men in power from business to political power they have the right to treat women as they please, not the women we are to bow down live with the nightmare. i decided to no longer suffer in silence but men like adam croasdell we stand up to or say no to feel they are the real victims and, as such, do not need to change their behavior and continue the cycle of abuse making it worse and enlist others to abuse their victims. adam croasdell is one of the many men during the #metoo era included in some of the most shameful chapters in the history of the united states because it shows his complicity and what men of his caliber will do to hurt women and hide it. 
#nomore #adamcroasdell #eccarius #ignisscientia #lordbothwell #actor #voiceactor #ffxv #preacher #reign #vampire #supernatural #losangeles #women #supportwomen #timesup

text:
google announced that it has fired 48 employees for sexual harassment in the past two years and sent them away without severance packages, hours after a news report stated that it had protected some male executives facing sexual misconduct allegations and offered them large sums to leave the company.

the surprise disclosure on thursday came in an email to google employees from ceo sundar pichai. it was a direct response to a new york times report that the company had dismissed the executive in charge of its android software for sexual misconduct in 2014 and paid him handsomely to leave.#metoo #metoomovement #google #us #india #sexualmisconduct #newyorktimes #thehindu

text:
forgiving is easier said then done. .

itâ€™s more of a practice if you ask me.  you canâ€™t  just forgive and forget.  or at least i canâ€™t. .

every time a bad memory comes up you feel everything for the first time. .

so forgiveness is a something that i have to work at all the freakin time. .

when mike passed i was so angry with him.  we had a deal!! .

we were suppose to grow old together.  we could handle anything life threw at us, as long as we had each other, we would figure out a way to get through it.  we were best friends.  i could see 20 more years down the road easily. .

youâ€™ll see us as kids on the next slide â¡ï¸ and then over 30 years later. .

i found myself all alone for the first time in my life.  i had no one that i could share my deepest fears with.  i had to learn to first forgive myself in order to heal. .

forgive myself for the anger and everything that hides behind that. .

#meditation helps me a lot!  my morning meditation relaxes me and the afternoon one heals me.  iâ€™m having trouble getting the 2nd one in.  but iâ€™m continuing to work at it. .

do you or do you know someone that #mediates regularly?  iâ€™d love to hear about your success. . . . .

text: qte: "here is a story from my book that i reread this morning in the wake of this brutal confirmation process. wherever you are lisa, i stand with you. what should have been an ordinary post-game interview for 26 year old boston herald reporter lisa olson quickly devolved into a divisive watershed moment for her career and the new england patriots. on september 17th, 1990 lisa had been covering the new england #patriots for a few months, and on that day, she went into the patriotsâ€™ locker room to interview a player about an injury. lisa suddenly found herself surrounded by three players: robert perryman, michael timpson, and zeke mowatt. mowatt allegedly stood in front of her, an arms-length away, fondled his genitals and taunted, â€œis this what you want? do you want to take a bite out of this?â€ the other two crowded around her, naked and making lewd gestures other players yelled â€œgive her what she wants! give her what she wants!â€ she fled the room shaken and furious at the experience, telling people magazine in an interview, "i didn't know whether to scream or break down and cry. it was a premeditated mind #rape. . after a few minutes, i gave up trying to interview maurice, thanked him and walked away. i felt total, blind rage." . . . then-owner of the patriots, victor kian ii, responded to the accusations by saying â€œi canâ€™t disagree with the playersâ€™ actions.â€ he blamed the incident on the herald, claiming they had â€œasked for troubleâ€ when they assigned a female reporter to the beat. he didnâ€™t spare the press his feelings about olson either, reportedly calling her a â€œclassic bitch.â€ an investigation was launched into the incident and as a result, olson was subjected to an avalanche of obscene phone calls and hate mail from patriots fans. her tires were slashed and her home was burglarizedâ€”she was left a note that said, â€œleave boston or die.â€ fearing for her safety, olson fled to australia. she remained there for six years writing for the sydney daily telegraph mirror." via @theunsungheroines #metoo #lisaolsen #lockerroomtalk #packmentality #brettkavanaugh #markjudge #christineblaseyford #susancollins #gop  #stopkavanaugh via:-@hang_tenj_

text:
u.s. president donald trump's former aide steve bannon sought to use personal information collected online to promote "a culture war," a whistleblower christopher wiley on now-defunct political data firm cambridge analytica told u.s. senators on wednesday.

bannon, a former cambridge analytica vice president, "saw cultural warfare as a means to create enduring change in american politics," testified christopher wylie, who says information about tens of millions of facebook (fb.o) users ended up in cambridge analytica's hands.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies. 
they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green, author
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

text:
and she always obeyed. she followed. she gave in. she knew nothing else.

for as long as she knew, she always listened. and did as she was told. everything they said was followed.

but then, one day. there was a storm. a mighty one. and things changed. the trees shook and some gave way. and when things calmed down, she could sense a storm was brewing inside her. and it happened.

suddenly. 
in a moment.

she just stopped doing whatever they said. 
and did what she wanted.

it is not clear whether her life changed for the better. but it was obvious to all that she lived happily ever after.

#storytime #kaamakethna #jungle #perspective #saturdayvibes #metoo

text: hi friends, we need to have a talk about white supremacy, patriarchy, and spiritual bypassing in the herbalism community. iâ€™m 2 years new to this community, and my journey is one of evolution. suffering from autoimmune related illness and needing help with boundaries to manage my trauma, i came looking to herbalism for help. i purchase items from @she_is_of_the_woods to help manage my stress, anxiety, and skin. i looked to @daniellelaporte for help reorient my life to the way i want to feel. i listened to @mythicmedicine podcasts and got exposed to interesting people and ideas like @laabejaherbs. from sofia i bought more medicines to help me feel embodied, process trauma, calm the nerves, and strengthen boundaries. when #metoo erupted i did not see these â€œhealersâ€ show solidarity. and when the susun weed abuse allegations came out, i saw a lot of defensiveness and cowardice. april and amber both ignored call-ins to ask them to be advocates of victims in the herbal medicine confluence-y community that includes kiva rose and wolf hardin. they instead have ignored victims. april set her followers on victims and claimed â€œmental healthâ€ reasons for why she didnâ€™t speak out. what about the mental health of victims?! now with the sean donahue victims speaking out, sophia is doing the same thing. this is so disappointing. i realize weâ€™re all just human, but what i donâ€™t understand is how people who have sought out the limelight by posting their lives on social media and cultivating large popular accounts can feel that they are exempt from doing real work to unpack white supremacy and patriarchy. they are doing real harm, and they have been given access to free tools to learn how to do this. please join me in ceasing to patronize them.

text:
#metoo coming to india... so happy finally a lot of stories are surfacing, for now... only females which are exposing, naming and shaming those that have been acting out of anyoneâ€™s comfort zone. 
i came to india the first time for a volunteer work in 2009 after i finished school & seeing the way indiaâ€™s/ mumbaiâ€™s culture, womenâ€™s rights and the general living quality has positively developed in the last 9years... thereâ€™s a humongous iceberg to address now. change is not gonna stop. 
i started modeling at the age of 6 in the industry and properly later on after i finished school in a lot of different countries... iâ€™ve seen my fare share of mainly men beyond reasonable age trying to abuse their positions of power or â€˜manhoodâ€™... more concerning tho the general mindset that exists towards women from society and we hold about our selves. the â€šrolesâ€™ we are suppose to play .. it goes way beyond the many producers/photographers/boyfriends/men who sexually or physically assaulted many of my friends&me & tried to take advantage of underage or vulnerable, way younger, a lot of times economically  disadvantaged girls... or the guys who act like â€šgood friends of yoursâ€™ who make you feel insecure, confused, bad for rejecting them or â€šforceâ€™ you into something you actually donâ€™t want... or in many cases the abusive boyfriends each of us had, who have been emotionally manipulative from the start... and you end up doing things you never wanted and they put you in positions you never thought you ever be in... itâ€™s a revolution in how women are seeing themselves and feel like they are supposed to be treated and taught. to say no... feel good about saying no, to not just serve the male gender & to finally own their own voice, after their entire lives of being shut down, kept quiet, â€˜be niceâ€™ , taken away and stripped of dignity and respect men had for thousands of years, women being reduced to their looks, bodies and their vaginas... voices that are not our ancestorâ€™s/traditionâ€™s/cultureâ€™s voices or the voice of shame, the voice of embarrassment and fear of retaliation... not the female voice deep down that is looking for a need for validation & approval from men...

text: i attended a red mass with rev shelly fayette in seattle early this week. it was a healing mass in honor of survivors of sexual violence. for an old buddhist like me, i felt a bit of an interloper, entering the church. but it was deeply moving to receive the blessings of this big hearted & down to earth young woman priest. may healing blessings continue to ripple out & out & bathe us all - every atheist, every agnostic, every believer & unbeliever of every faith, & every tradition in the world - not one left behind. #revshellyfayette #metoo #worldpeace

ãƒ»ãƒ»ãƒ»
do you still miss her?

i was questioned this since the day we are not together. by my friends, by my relatives, by my readers and due to this sometimes by my mind as well.
but i can't still figure out the answer to it. i keep on retreating in my mind that answer to which is simply a "no". yes, it has been years now how can you still miss her? echoes my self-respect. but i noticed you are still a frequent visitor in my mind. you are that guest who pays a visit without notice and sometimes do stay a bit long. but it's fine now i am used to this behaviour of yours of leaving and staying as per your wish.

i won't hide and nor say it with pride but i still talk to you, sometimes on a moonless nights when past keeps on hammering and is hungry for my sleep. please don't feel happy and consider me as your mad lover. it does occupy my mind but my tormented yet stone like heart is unaffected.

you see, on the wall of my heart you are that nail which i have thrown long back, which was rusted and couldn't hold the portrait of our love. but yes the mark is still there, the hole is still there. i haven't made any efforts to paint it with new colours of emotions.

maybe i want it as it is. 
maybe i want you to remind me of my madness, 
maybe i want you as a memory only. 
maybe i want you in my stories. 
but just to confirm i am sure, i don't want you in this life again.

darshan sanghvi.
(@darshansanghvi28)
.
.
.

i will not hide and nor say it with pride but i still talk to you, sometimes on a moonless nights when past keeps on hammering and is hungry for my sleep. please do not feel happy and consider me as your mad lover. it does occupy my mind but my tormented yet stone like hea is unaffected.

you see, on the wall of my hea you are that nail which i have thrown long back, which was rusted and couldn't hold the porait of our love. but yes the mark is still there, the hole is still there. i have not made any effos to paint it with new colours of emotions.

maybe i want it as it is. 
maybe i want you to remind me of my madness, 
maybe i want you as a memory only. 
maybe i want you in my stories. 
but just to confirm i am sure, i do not want you in this life again.

darshan sanghvi.
(arshansanghvi28)
.
.
.

text:
the beauty behind you is that you create your own direction and are filled with life that no other being can replicate. the patterns in your universe are forever yours but sometimes figuring out the code to life can be exhausting.. this project surrounds our every day routine, the voices in our heads and the journey that creates knots in our minds and twists the vocabulary that we once knew so well...it is forever changing...it is a state and a void of feelings known towards the unknown. at times we feel unique and as we face uncertainties and share our lives with those we live with, we breathe....in silence, with weight and in darkness even when there is light.. 'the art of healing - takes a look at the beauty in our flaws and the strength in our weaknesses. it brings together the art, minds and souls of 3 women from different backgrounds, but the same understanding that healing, a thought not easy, is necessary and is something we all deserve.' - jessie. ...link to full editorial and article feature in bio. now featured in @browngirlmag

text: thank you to @ladiesfirstastoria (@singlegirlcookies & @nicolep1109) for a wonderful event tonight.  they had an incredibly talented group of women there for the panel of a sexual harassment workshop discussing the topics of street, workplace and interpersonal harassment.  it was informative and eye opening.  as many of you know, i left a very toxic work environment, what i hadnâ€™t mentioned before was that at my job at nyâ€™s top real estate brokerage company, a male coworker asked me a very inappropriate question and when i reported it, the female cfo made it a point to blame me and support him.  hr then retaliated against me and my compliant and lied about why i complained, blamed me and ended up giving me a warning.  i left abruptly as i mentioned before and wanted to just forget it and have it all behind me but i know now that i canâ€™t just let this be the end of it.  i need to do more.  i know everything happens for a reason and this one is so i can share my toxic experiences and be the support for other women in the workforce that i didnâ€™t receive.  women working in corporate especially in industries like mine, finance, already have it tough and we need to be there for each other not above one another. #womensupportingwomen #sexualharrassment #ladiesfirstastoria #lfa #astoria #womenspanel #womenempowerment @womenempower #metoo #metoomovement

text:
when kanchandevi jat was elected as the sarpanch of lakhola gram panchayat (sahara panchayat samiti, bhilwara block) four years ago, little did she know what was going to come her way within a few days. one day, while she was at her farm, two young girls came running to her for help. there was a group of goons in the forest area close to her farm that had attempted to molest them, but somehow they managed to escape and found kanchan on their way. she took the girls to the goons (who were drinking and gambling in their car), threatened them, gathered the nearby villagers at the farms who thrashed them, immediately called the police by dialling 101 (because she remembered from her ongoing training that 101 is an emergency helpline that works even without a mobile phone balance) and got them arrested. she has since then set such a high benchmark of courage against violence in her village that other girls and women have started speaking up and taking action just like her. at home she is as warm and hospitable as all mothers, while at work as fierce as a lioness. ğŸ‘ŠğŸ¼ what canâ€™t be achieved with collective strength and wisdom of a woman?! if only we saw more of such examples even in the cities #electedtolead
#womeninpolitics
#deepeningdemocracy
#genderequality

#sdgs51016

#localdevelopment  #safespaces #enablingaccess #claimingpoliticalspaces #ruralwomen #daretolead #womensupportingwomen #metooindia #metoo #violenceagainstwomen #leadingbyexample

text: as most of you already know, on october 26th 2013, my life changed forever..... ğŸ˜” i was raped. it left me broken, lost, and afraid, with so many problems from ptsd to depression just eating away at me. but, i am a survivor, the daughter of a king(god), and a warrior! ğŸ’ª i got through it all with god and his blessing of incredible, amazing friends/family in my life! ğŸ’– i have grown and learned soooo much throughout these years of getting through that and all the rough times that occur throughout life because every day may not be perfect and may be full of battles, but by continuously looking at any and all blessings (no matter how small) and by never giving up you will be able to see just how beautiful life can be! ğŸŒˆ a few things i have learned that i would love to share with you today is this: when you feel like your whole world is falling apart, when you need just one minute to breathe, when you feel like itâ€™s getting too hard to handle. that is when you keep going, keep fighting, take one step at a time, and never give up! ğŸ’ your story isnâ€™t over yet and this rough battle right now is part of your story, the part that you use to grow from, learn from, and use to inspire yourself and others! âœ¨ you are soooo valuable, so donâ€™t let anyone bring you down just because they have an inability to see your incredible worth! ğŸ’ you are strong, you are irreplaceable, you matter, and you belong here! â˜€ï¸ the sun will come out and shine bright again, just keep holding on! â­ï¸ #yougotthis #countyourblessings #livelovelaugh #nevergiveup #youarestrong #survivor #metoo #youareirreplaceable #bethebestversionofyou #godisgood #youareloved #youarenotalone #lifeisbeautiful

âœ§complex ptsd criteria: part 1âœ§
now that we've done a brief overview on how complex ptsd differs from ptsd, we'd like to take a much deeper look into individualized criteria for c-ptsd - how the condition truly manifests into one's entire world and self-view, beyond just the posttraumatic symptoms.
.
the first of these criteria is "alternations in emotion regulation". emotions are challenging for many people, but they are especially difficult for those who've survived complex trauma. for most, showing emotions wasn't safe. survivors were sent mixed messages and given different responses, often violent ones, for each display of emotion. just as things seemed predictable, they would change. what was allowed one day wasn't tolerated the next. now, as an adult, re-experiencing traumatic content, including dissociated emotions, via flashbacks and intrusive symptoms can take this familiar challenge to the next level. survivors may feel their emotions are unpredictable, all-consuming, and either come at full speed or endless lulls of numbness or apathy.
.
luckily, there are great coping skills that make emotion regulation much more feasible (there's even an entire category of dbt dedicated to it)! we deeply empathize with all of you who are struggling to just understand or name your feelings, let alone feel them and then navigate them gracefully! we send you our utmost compassion, with a promise that it can get better.
.
stay tuned for our next posts as we discuss the rest!
.
ğŸ’œğŸ’™ğŸ’›
.
[as a note: c-ptsd is still not formally recognized in the dsm, but these criteria have existed and been used by practitioners for awhile despite the lack of a diagnostic code.]
.
.
.
.
.

text:
review â€“ women talking, miriam toewsğŸ‡¨ğŸ‡¦
â€¢
women talking is miriam toewsâ€™s fictionalized response to the true story of the rape and sexual assault of over 130 women (under anaesthetic) in a bolivian mennonite colony in the early 2000s. in her novel, toews imagines the women talking about what to do next, as seen through the eyes of the teacher who is taking minutes for them. having grown up in a mennonite community herself, toews writes characters and dialogue that feel authentic and draw the reader into the hayloft where they talk.
â€¢
women talking is a book about courage in the face of sexual assault, isolation, and disempowerment. in some ways, little â€œhappensâ€ in the book; mostly the women talk. but indeed, so much happens as they unpack whatâ€™s happened to them, question the tenets of their faith and the limitations their society places on them, and then bravely discover and ignite their own power and agency.
â€¢
women talking reminded me of the memoir educated. in isolated communities, women and children are vulnerable as they can be denied the education and broader community connections which enable them to evaluate their lives and to seek the help of others. the heroism of the women in toewsâ€™s book is therefore all the more astonishing.
â€¢
the isolated setting emphasizes many of the broader issues being discussed by the #metoo movement. the womenâ€™s discussion echoes and amplifies the internal debate of many victims of abuse: ultimately, to stay or to leave....and what to do about the children.
â€¢
although short (only 216 pages), i found women talking hard to read, not because of the writing (toewsâ€™s prose is effortless), but because of the tough subject matter. itâ€™s an important contribution to the current conversation about sexual assault.
â€¢
(question for others whoâ€™ve read it: did you notice the coloured letters on the cover? i thought nothing of them until i looked at the spine and i noticed they were reproduced there and spelled out â€œlove angersâ€.)
â€¢
â€¢
â€¢

text:
2018 must be so confusing to white people. tomi lahern was fired for being too liberal; megan kelly was fired for being too racist and white men no longer work anywhere of importance ...and all at the hands of eachother
.

it's so fucking strange
.

it's like this perfect storm of panic. people who have spent their entire lives working towards a single goal? over, simply bc the lack of conversation that white america is comfortable with. white people perpetually confuse killing someone off with authority
.

there is an *entire* history carved from the same stone, and still white people haven't gotten it down yet. always choose the conversation, and stay engaged
.

i *absolutely do not panic* over anything really, but when you panic? you kill everything in sight. it's unnecessary
.

and when i say i don't panic? i mean never. i was diagnosed with a brain tumor while living in thailand on my birthday and nobody spoke english. always stay calm so logic can enter. to assume that a comment hurt enough feelings to end a career is ridiculous
.

and bc the target was black, black people will be indirectly held accountable for this. it's just a pathetic extension of ...the murderous consequences of white mediocrity
.

hurt feelings will just never be illegal, and there should be a standard. but, bc the white girl movement was all, "i'm 3 years older then aziz ansari, but when we met at the soho house and got very drunk 2gether ğŸ˜‹ğŸ˜…ğŸ˜ğŸ˜š and i willing went home with him he touched my breast!! #metoo!!" and twitter is like #hero! #hearmeroar!! once again, white girls setting the trend for the *complete measure of misogyny*
.

and worse yet? nobody knows this is even a thing but black people
.

we live in america; the english language isn't extensive enough for us to avoid making errors in public, on live tv or to our mothers, husbands, lovers... the infant you think can't understand you and the list continues to everyone, everywhere
.

looks like i'll have to feed meg newmans kids or hit her off with some of my winnings bc if smart and white megan kelly can't work? eh, mediocre minded and white meg newman is also a definite "hard no"
.

text: in a world where â€œconsentâ€ seems to be a dirty word, i was inspired to write this song (link in bio). when i feel that my rights as a woman are being, now more than ever, attacked, undermined, and not only ignored but dismissed as an issue, i respond in anger. this song, for me, is more about a battle cry. starting with the abuse from both her attacker and the public, and ending with a hard â€œno moreâ€. you can laugh it off, you can say itâ€™s not real, but rape is real and the fight for womenâ€™s rights is real and valid. a womanâ€™s body is her body and she has a right to her body, a right to birth control, a right to affordable feminine health and preventative care services, a right to sexual consent, a right to equal pay, a right to every right a man has, a right to being a woman and living without fear of being groped and harassed or assaulted. and on top of all of that, a right to come forward and speak of her attack without being maligned, blamed and shamed. no one is asking to be treated special, just to be treated equally. i donâ€™t agree with all of the actions taken via the #metoo movement; i think there are a few people who got swept up in it who didnâ€™t deserve to; but itâ€™s a start, and i genuinely hope the cause and the conversation will continue and end in real change.

text:
they say â€œyou canâ€™t have it all, you will have to choose between motherhood and your careerâ€
-
feminism and motherhood have a complicated relationship. radical feminist shulamith firestone think that women would never truly be free of patriarchy until they were freed from the yoke of reproduction.
-
in an article for @bustle , @ejdickson explains that â€œmillennial women are still forced to decide between deeply dissatisfying options. choose motherhood over work, and they lose out on the self-empowerment, personal fulfillment, and financial independence a career affords; -
choose work over motherhood, and they lose an experience that could give their lives new color and dimension and meaning; try to have both, and they end up embittered and exhausted, operating on half-empty at all times.â€
-
â€œbetween the cost of childcare, limited parental leave policies, work and motherhood have become financially, logistically, and physically incompatible.
in itself, the fact that many well-educated women view professional success as key to happiness, rather than marriage and babies, is undoubtedly a good thing. but it also makes the choice to leave your career and work identity behind even harder.â€
*
*
*

text:
gratitude to sister-survivor tarana burke/ @taranajaneen for inviting me to contribute to her guest edited #metoo (@metoomvmt) series of articles, and also profiles (penned by @kibasolomon920f) of some of the many sister-comrades in the anti-violence movement: indira henard/ @indiramassie (@officialdcrapecrisiscenter ), kalimah johnson/@kalimahthelocmama (@sashacenter), joanne smith/ @joannen.smith (@ggenyc ), and scheherazade tillet/@sherphotographs and salamishah tillet @salamishah (@alongwalkhome) featured in the november 2018 edition of @essence magazine. tarana asked me to share steps that we can each take to end sexual violence. i offered 7 steps:
*
believe survivors
respond vigorously
quit blaming victims
support men and boys too
stop pathologizing the lgbtq community
teach body sovereignty
explore survivor-centered accountability
*

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
it has been months since i have heard from you, since you snapchatted me one morning out of the blue- without prompting, an unsolicited video of you masturbating. i didnt respond. you sent a sexual cartoon immediately after, maybe to make light of your first video? i didn't respond. i didnt really know what to say- the video had catapulted beyond our flirtatious exchanges of texts and the occasional sexy photo into something all too familiar- it felt, to put it simply, cheap and gross. it took me about a week to realize you had blocked me on all social media. 
i was gobsmacked, shocked at the childish move on your part; then, that familiar voice eeked its way in, that voice that many women know well and few men seem to be accustomed to: "what did you do? you must have done something wrong, obviously, otherwise he wouldn't have had to block you." i shrugged it off after a time, my girlfriends did some diggingÂ and sent me screenshots of his recent posts, one featuring him and a girl, accompanied by all the romantic emojis . "ah, so that's what happened." again i was annoyed, and felt a tinge of sympathy for the girl, but i quickly forgot about it. until saturday.

late saturday night iÂ was driving home and at a stoplight and as i glanced across the street, there you were on the opposite corner, your giant frame outlined by the streetlight. i couldnt believe it and before i had time to think i was pulling a u-turn and pulling up to the gas station near where you were standing, getting out of the car and yelling your name in a question mark; you turned, and in an irritatingly casual unaffected way, sauntered over. god help me, i gave you a hug, and kept my tone light and asked what happened as if i didnt know. you told me you "fell into a girlfriend situation" and that she had discovered that you were texting me and didn't like it. you mentionedÂ nothing of your own misconduct, nor anything about blocking me. the conversation continued as i inquired about her, all the while iÂ hovered above my body and imagined myself chewing you out, calling you a coward and making you aware of the inappropriate nature of your behavior. (cont in comments)

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn
