text:
this is what depression looks like.  iâ€™ve lived my life acting like i was ok and talking to people about my experiences to try to help them to not live as a victim and i in turn lived my life as a victim. iâ€™ve always said that i wasnâ€™t but i always have been. for the past 20 years i have hidden my pain behind my smile. iâ€™ve numbed it with drugs. iâ€™ve also not allowed myself to be who i want to be. i was abused. as a kid, then again as a teenager, and again as an adult. those experiences have scarred me. iâ€™ve tried to forgive those who have hurt me so that i can move on, but part of me never has moved on. my weight has been an issue for a long time. every time i lose some weight i become extremely insecure. i get that way because i feel that if i look appealing, it will happen again. so i gain the weight back. iâ€™m fucking tired of it. iâ€™m not happy with the way i look and i want to look good for myself and not live in fear of what others may do. 
those who know me know that i am very open about sex, and i sometimes dress provocatively. after being a victim of sexual abuse, i had the choice to either be scared of sex or to have no understanding of sex and just abuse it. i chose to understand it, and understand the power i had to either have it or not have it. iâ€™m trying to teach myself that i can be sexy without having the fear of being abused. itâ€™s not easy though. some days i feel it and iâ€™m all yes be sexy, fuck what anyone thinks, other days, most days, i want to be the person nobody looks at and nobody wants.
iâ€™m trying to move on and past things so that i can be a better influence to the girls.  i also chose to educate myself so that i can educate my daughters so that they may live a life free of this type of abuse. 
again, some days are easier than others. 
what iâ€™m asking, and why iâ€™m sharing this is because i donâ€™t feel like this is talked about much. especially with children. men and women who abuse people are getting away with it, and the victims are left to feel shame and disgust for the rest of their lives. and quite frankly, itâ€™s pissing me off.... read the rest in photos. #metoo #scared  #survivor #weightloss #depressionquotes #instadaily

art market per raw rome art week 2018 a cura di sonia vecchio e dario calÃ¬ ( https://www.facebook.com/events/1506289546139688/ ) presso calidarium gallery - vicolo del piede,18 rm.
open studio di monica argentino (@miss.alicemoon.artist )in occasione del vernissage/23 ottobre con â€œflowerincage _ performance art _body painting liveâ€ di monica argentino "una riflessione accurata fatta di forme,colori e corpi tangibili, sulla violenza di genere attraverso l'arte."
flowerincage ispirata alla mostra pittorica personale di monica argentino "chimera: le forme del male".
chimera affronta la violenza sulle donne piÃ¹ specificamente in ambito affettivo, la loro dipendenza psicologica con il carnefice, spesso fino alla morte. 
in flowerincage si vuole rappresentare la capacita' delle donne di trasformare il dolore in forza. 
cosi' l'artista trasforma il corpo della modella in un fiore simbolico, violato nel silenzio di una societa' troppe volte cieca, carceriere del suo malessere, ma che resiste ed esiste con la sua bellezza.
una riflessione sulle violenze di genere e sulla resistenza e resilienza delle donne.

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin

- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking â€˜ugh. totally uglyâ€™ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

men must hold the intention to end all wars ğŸ”¥ .

as men we have been at war with ourselves since the beginning of recorded history. by fist and knee, sword and steed, rifle and cannon, tank and missile; we have plunged entire civilizations into chaos and calamity, causing unfathomable pain and suffering to millions of human lives throughout history. .

is our penchant for war due to our intrinsic savagery, orÂ is it born of societal conditioning which instills in us a false allegiance rooted partly in fear, to authorities who are upheld as more powerful than us because of their physical stature, hoarded wealth, social status or inherited privilege? .

maybe both but consider the truth that the vast majority of human beings do not want to die nor do we want to kill. yet when we are threatened, coerced, or pressured by perceived authorities, seemingly reasonable men and women have throughout time degraded to committing horrific atrocities in the name of following orders. .

add to this the fact that history is filled with ego-maniacal leaders who have almost always been men that were hell bent on accumulating more power/resources and reveled in death and destruction. fast forward to the present day where we are certainly better off in many respects, yet some things have not changed much at all. .

men are still at war with each other, in literal wars fought with armies, insurgents, drones, and bombs, but also wars waged in the courtroom, sports arenas, corporate boardrooms, etc. because the patriarchal systems of power keep humanity divided against one another, historically by elevating the status and importance of men while simultaneously diminishing women, as well as inculcating an "us vs. them" mentality from our earliest years. .

this mass programming which capitalizes on our survival instinct coupled with the illusion of scarcity promulgated by the elite, and reinforced through emphasis on competition over cooperation in schooling will ensure the perpetuation of power not in the hands of the wisest or most visionary, but often those who have the least scruples and the greatest lust for power. .

text: when i was in the market for an f40, these photos came up from @bingosports_official in japan.  i loved how menacing it looked in black but thought i better buy a nice classiche certified red car.  fast forward a couple of years and i just kept watching this black monster.  glad i was able to make a deal and bring it to canada and enjoy it.  they had all the factory parts shipped along with the car.  i think they did a great job of making a jdm from a classic.  i guess @rrrawlings saw it and it inspired them to build the gmg car from a salvage f40.  very cool build they made famous.  #checatz #ferrari #ferrarifriday #f40 #blackcarsmatter #notgasmonkey #gmg

flex friday goes to jamie lee curtis. curtis reprised the role of laurie strode for the latest film in the halloween franchise. the film opened this weekend and brought in a whopping $75m in one weekend. this was the most from any of the films in the franchise.
-
whats significant is was that this made halloween (2018) the biggest horror movie opening of all time with a female lead, and even more significant, the biggest movie opening ever with a female lead over 55.
-
hopefully the tide is changing in hollywood, often criticised for its ageism, whitewashing, and of course, the industry that prompted the #metoo movement. in light of this, jamie lee curtis' achievement is one that should be celebrated and was therefore an easy choice for flex friday this week. and with horror being one of my favourite genre's, this panda will definitely be going to check out the latest instalment of the halloween movies.
-
happy halloween pandas.

i got a lot of stick about how â€œpro-voteâ€ i was about our presidential election (and referendum) we had today. none taken personally obviously â€“ i get it, i do. i do not however understand why someone would not place a ballot in what is our a functioning democracy. we areÂ  not living in a country (of which none i will name but there are so many..) where our voting rights are hindered, repressed or even obsolete. our vote actually counts. a vote is a voice that is heard. that is democracy. most people know i am very interested in politics and the socio-/geo-political aspects that go with it â€“ but this is not why i cared so much about our election. i cared about it because it is for our own country. you should care about your vote because your government actually cares about it. it is not repressing or ignoring it. use your vote. use your voice. because it is heard â€“ and this is something that should be valued â€“ especially now.
.

text:
i wrote "believe" two years ago after my brother-in-law josh died. then later in 2016, the song took on a new meaning to me after the presidential election. it felt bigger than my own personal story. music is powerful and magical in that way; it transcends one specific event. once iâ€™ve written a song and put it out in the world, itâ€™s no longer â€œmine.â€ itâ€™s yours and ours. and right now, with the midterms approaching and living in a year of #metoo and political discord, the timing of this release feels kismet. ğŸ•Š

if you've preordered on @pledgemusic , i've uploaded a piano/vocal demo of the song for you to have. i'm fond of the raw quality of the recording, but i do miss those @violaseh strings! if you havenâ€™t already, and it's within your means and preference, i'd love to have you join the unkindness flock by preordering on pledge. i'll be posting exclusives like this demo and bts footage along the way to pledgers. link in bio.

i hope you've been enjoying the song. stay tuned for news on the second single, released next month(!) love you all. (and thank you @ventsmagazine for chatting with me about the story of â€œbelieve!â€) xo m ğŸ“¸:@maddytalias

text:
qanon fans are applying this same participatory behavior that we have celebrated in fiction fandom to real-world political drama. and why not? the boundaries between politics and entertainment have been collapsing for years. the entire trump presidency operates like reality tv, completely divorced from any real stakes or substance.

thatâ€™s what makes this all so terrifying. do these people really believe that tom hanks and hillary clinton are personally running a massive pedophilia ring? really??? but consider this: trump announced at a rally this week that the farmers being harmed by his stupid trade war had told him â€œwe can take it.â€ no actual farmers said that to him. we all know that. but itâ€™s a little thing, just part of the story we are all interacting with.

the pulsating heart of the qanon theory is not a lunatic fringe denying the real consequences of a failing presidency. the heart of it is a devoted fan base constructing elaborate theories to make the story more fun and engaging. and if you start from the premise that nothing government does matters, then itâ€™s easy to come along for the ride. thereâ€™s no real difference between hillary clinton and the smoke monster. theyâ€™re both just characters on the television.

thatâ€™s what alarms me most about the growth of qanon. itâ€™s not that these people are unhinged and possibly armed. itâ€™s that weâ€™ve lost the capacity to treat civics, governance, and public affairs as though they have actual stakes with actual consequences. the premise of the trump presidency is that nothing matters, so you should root for your side and heckle the opposing team. he encourages his supporters to treat democrats and journalists like a rival fan base.

david karpf
medium

text:
qanon fans are applying this same participatory behavior that we have celebrated in fiction fandom to real-world political drama. and why not? the boundaries between politics and entertainment have been collapsing for years. the entire trump presidency operates like reality tv, completely divorced from any real stakes or substance.

thatâ€™s what makes this all so terrifying. do these people really believe that tom hanks and hillary clinton are personally running a massive pedophilia ring? really??? but consider this: trump announced at a rally this week that the farmers being harmed by his stupid trade war had told him â€œwe can take it.â€ no actual farmers said that to him. we all know that. but itâ€™s a little thing, just part of the story we are all interacting with.

the pulsating heart of the qanon theory is not a lunatic fringe denying the real consequences of a failing presidency. the heart of it is a devoted fan base constructing elaborate theories to make the story more fun and engaging. and if you start from the premise that nothing government does matters, then itâ€™s easy to come along for the ride. thereâ€™s no real difference between hillary clinton and the smoke monster. theyâ€™re both just characters on the television.

thatâ€™s what alarms me most about the growth of qanon. itâ€™s not that these people are unhinged and possibly armed. itâ€™s that weâ€™ve lost the capacity to treat civics, governance, and public affairs as though they have actual stakes with actual consequences. the premise of the trump presidency is that nothing matters, so you should root for your side and heckle the opposing team. he encourages his supporters to treat democrats and journalists like a rival fan base.

david karpf

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since the start.

steve bannon left the wh august last year and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit the hijacked party of puppets is obviously just business as usual.
